Introduction¶

In this data story, we used the dataset which was complied for the Philosophy Data Project to develop potential features. The data intend to capture huge amount of famous texts wrote by differnt authors, collected by different titles, and originated from different schools. Generally, this kind of analysis will focus on the text, however, there still can have some numeric features. We are going to not only focusing on the texts, but also the groups who wrote the texts. More specifically, I would like to find out how the philosopers are different from each other and also the texts they wrote. In the process of the this report, in the purpose of presenting a more detailed analysis, we would like to put splotlight on two schools and authors in those schools.

It's hard to define who are the greatest, but based on this dataset, we definitely can do some reseach on other quantitative aspects. Part1: Date¶

Which time period appeared most texts and edited texts?¶

Let's observe the original publication date and corpus edition date we have here.

In [6]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
df['original_publication_date'].value_counts().plot(kind = 'bar')
plt.title('original_publication_date')
Out[6]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'original_publication_date')

Obviously, -320 and -350 are two periods that provided most of the texts. The strange thing is this dataset doest not contain any texts between the period of 170 and 1600+, but it is hard to explore only based on the data. And the plot here is automaticly sorted by the number of texts which is not perfect to find the features through time. Thus, let do some adjustments.

In [7]:
df_date = df.sort_values(by=['original_publication_date'])
df_date['count'] = 1
plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
df_date.groupby(by = ['original_publication_date']).sum()['count'].plot(kind = 'bar')
plt.title('original_publication_date')
Out[7]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'original_publication_date')

By this chart, we can see the volume of quotes well up from -350 and topped at -320. After that is a sharply dumping and have some siginificant rebounce in some years but still have large gap compare to -350 and -320. This feature does make sense. The beginning of a subject usually from the fisrt major discoveries. Then, many new and relevant discoveries emerge, yet after a period of development they inevitably hit a bottleneck, making it difficult to continue to generate new ideas that are completely different from those of their predecessors. This is also the reason why we see dump.Whenever a bottleneck is broken because of social development, another wave of telltale development is ushered in, which is why there is a bounce from time to time. Let's continue to focus on the edition date.

# define plot function
def color_boxplot(data, color, pos=[0], ax=None):
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    bp = ax.boxplot(data, patch_artist=True,  showmeans=True,showfliers = False, positions=pos)
    for item in ['boxes', 'whiskers', 'fliers', 'medians', 'caps']:
        plt.setp(bp[item], color=color)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
bp1 = color_boxplot(analytic.word_count, 'green', [1])

Data Analysis¶

As of now, in this part, we are going to explore several topics which we think are interesting and can not be solved through simple processing the data. These questions need some further analysis. We are going to firstly start with the topic we just mentioned by the end of data overview part, it does require us to perform a mutiple sample t test. We will assume the texts are picked randomly and they distribute approximately normal according to Central Limit Theorom. And here is how it goes:

Apply t tests to the word counts of analytic school and german idealism school¶

In [80]:
# Conducting two-sample ttest
result = pg.ttest(analytic.word_count,
                  idealism.word_count,
                  correction=True)

print(result)

                T           dof alternative  p-val            CI95%   cohen-d  \

       BF10  power

Based on the test result, we can significantly reject the null hypothesis which says the two samples have the same mean value, and justify our naive conclusion in the previous part.

By using school as category, we find that there are 3 out of 3 pairs result in rejecting the null hypothesis which represents there does have some difference between those comparisons. However, the concern is, does the proportion like 3/3 and 20/21 robust enough to support this conclusion? It worth more further exploration. Another concern is there probably are variables that also effect the sentences length except the two we just explored. For example, the publication date that exists in the orignal dataset. Since each auhor and school has its lifespan, it not a good idea to observe the influence of time only scale to some authors and schools. Thus, we are going to check this in a more macro perspective.

Does the sentences length also different through time period?¶

Since the date variable is quantitative, I would like to use some methods from time series analysis here. If we can prove that sentence length has some relationship with the publication date, it can say that sentences length changes as different date. However, the date data we have here is not continuous and have a strong gap, it definitely will ruin the regression as the following plot shows.

More authors is good?¶

One thing that people may miss out in this dataset is, each school has different number of members. However, the proportion of total texts that each school contain are also different. The common sense is more people, more productions. Is this common sense still can apply to the wrold of philosopy? Let find the answer. My naive guess is it tend to be more texts, the base logic is more people trigger more discussions, more discussion will derive more ideas, more ideas more textts. Before we start doing the reseach, two outliers, Aristotle and Plato, need to be dropped from the data. It is one hundred percent not fair to compare these two outliers with others.

How different the texts are between different school? Or even no difference.¶

As we mentioned before, we are going to find out the core value of each school in order to verify their uniqueness on writing texts. It is a reseach targeting on text. Thus, we gonna introduce wordcoulds, which will show some frequent words that be used in texts from sample schools. Again, we will scale to two schools as our previous analysis, which are analytic and german idealism.

# function for sentiment analysis
def SentimentAnlysis(sentence):
    sentAnalyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer() 
    sentDict = sentAnalyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
    
    if sentDict['compound'] >= 0.05:
        return "positive"
    elif sentDict['compound'] <= -0.05 :
        return "negative"
    else:
        return "neutral"

Conclusion¶

Oeverall, we do obtain some tangible results after exploring the dataset. We firstly focus on the distribution of catergorical variables and numeric variables. We found that there are two outstanding authors which produced extraordinary amount of texts, and the collections in their names also contained huge amount of quotes. In the perspective of school, analytic and german idealism provided strong proportion of texts. This also make us to choose these two schools for our more detailed analysis. In addition, we realize that the time variables in this data is inconsistent and we failed to apply some time series method on that. However, we still find some features from that. In the research regarding the sentences length, while the charts showed us not that much differences of sentences length between each categorical sample, the t-test results justify the truth to us. I am glad the choice of investigating this problem not only using visualization but also the hypothesis test. Besides those, we also explore whether the school with more members can wrote more texts. By the end, we used sentiment analysis function to summary the general attitude of the texts from analytic and german idealism. I hope those results are agreeable and make sense to all audiences.

Although we pretend several useful conclusions, there still have some unfixed topics due to the constrain of dataset and our data analysis skills. It appears that we can do better with more data and more reference.
